text.tspan: GNOME Contacts: What does a contact look like?
Some people may find a contact easier visually, some prefer to read through text. We need to empower both groups.
First, we need a photo of our contact
and his name. Both are key elements
The result however looks a bit misaligned
and won't help visual people to find their
contact. Therefore we want to give each
contact tile an appearance of a rectangle.
Great, now that looks quite nice! But the
lower status line doesn't make much sense.
We came up with 2 ideas, how we could
make use of that line. The first one is to
put contact buttons in it, to allow users to
directly get in touch with their chosen contact.
The second was to put a specific text in it.
While it might be a cool idea to have direct contact
buttons, we soon run into the first problem: With many
contacts, colors don't help to find a contact quickly, they
Okay then, let's get rid of colors. We still have two
1) What does a specific icon mean? is it IM, SMS?
What if I prefer Jabber instead of GTalk? Many users
will probably not know, so this could be a problem.
2) If a user has several accounts of the same service, e.g.
multiple e-mail addresses, how can we use the correct
one? The answer simply is, we can't. Solutions would be
to either take always the primary account of a service
So icons alone don't seem to be the way to go. When putting
text, we always need to know the context the user
is in, to show the right information there. For example:
Best of both worlds: both have their advantages
and disadvantages, so we came up with a solution,
that uses the best things of each solution.
